TY  - JOUR
T1  - Selection Dynamics, Asymptotic Stability, and Adaptive Behavior
AU  - Van Huyck, John B.
AU  - Cook, Joseph P.
AU  - Battalio, Raymond C.
Y1  - 1994/10/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261961
DO  - 10.1086/261961
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 975
EP  - 1005
VL  - 102
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Selection dynamics are often used to distinguish stable and unstable equilibria. This is particularly useful when multiple equilibria prevent a priori comparative static analysis. This paper reports an experiment designed to compare the accuracy of the myopic best-response dynamic and an inertial selection dynamic. The inertial selection dynamic makes more accurate predictions about the observed mutual best-response outcomes.
AB  - Selection dynamics are often used to distinguish stable and unstable equilibria. This is particularly useful when multiple equilibria prevent a priori comparative static analysis. This paper reports an experiment designed to compare the accuracy of the myopic best-response dynamic and an inertial selection dynamic. The inertial selection dynamic makes more accurate predictions about the observed mutual best-response outcomes.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261961
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261961
Y2  - 2024/03/23
